00:20:00,499 --> 00:20:04,902
- That was pretty good.
- You were really good.

235
00:20:33,232 --> 00:20:35,757
Hey, I'm sorry I'm late.
I'm gonna go up and change.

236
00:20:35,834 --> 00:20:37,859
Right.

237
00:20:37,936 --> 00:20:41,667
- Dad work late tonight?
- Yeah, looks that way.

238
00:20:43,976 --> 00:20:46,604
Guess whatever he's working on,
he must like it.

239
00:20:46,678 --> 00:20:50,671
- Why do you say that?
- He seems happier lately.

240
00:20:54,186 --> 00:20:56,279
Does he?

241
00:21:02,261 --> 00:21:03,387
I called the Halston people
in New York.

242
00:21:03,462 --> 00:21:07,023
We're gonna have trouble getting more
stock in. Everything's on back-order.

243
00:21:07,099 --> 00:21:10,557
Look, Carolyn, I'm gonna need you
to go to New York and sweet-talk them.

244
00:21:10,636 --> 00:21:13,127
- Can you leave tomorrow?
- No.

245
00:21:13,205 --> 00:21:15,264
Why not?

246
00:21:15,340 --> 00:21:18,275
My husband is having an affair.

247
00:21:21,680 --> 00:21:23,614
How do you know that?

248
00:21:23,682 --> 00:21:26,446
I picked up the receiver last night
to phone a friend,

249
00:21:26,518 --> 00:21:31,683
not knowing that Greg was already
on the other line in the den.

250
00:21:31,757 --> 00:21:33,782
He was whispering.

251
00:21:34,526 --> 00:21:36,551
What was he whispering?

252
00:21:36,628 --> 00:21:38,721
I don't know.

253
00:21:38,797 --> 00:21:42,358
I was so scared I hung up
before I could hear anything.

254
00:21:42,434 --> 00:21:46,370
Well, there's lots of other reasons
why he could be whispering.

255
00:21:46,438 --> 00:21:50,875
I mean, maybe he didn't wanna
wake up the kids. Huh?

256
00:21:50,942 --> 00:21:56,539
Or he could be planning a surprise for you.
I mean, your birthday's coming up, isn't it?

257
00:21:58,617 --> 00:22:01,347
In two weeks.

258
00:22:06,391 --> 00:22:08,484
That's it.

259
00:22:11,296 --> 00:22:15,596
Take a breath, go get yourself a brownie
in the kitchen, just chill. It's gonna be fine.

260
00:22:15,667 --> 00:22:17,658
OK.

261
00:22:18,570 --> 00:22:21,164
- Euh!
- Ooh-hoo-hoo!

262
00:22:21,239 --> 00:22:23,605
You silly goose, you.

263
00:22:25,677 --> 00:22:28,271
She'll be divorced by Easter.

264
00:22:39,291 --> 00:22:42,351
Come on, John.
Join the warm-up.

265
00:23:21,533 --> 00:23:22,522
Ow!

266
00:23:22,601 --> 00:23:25,593
- Jesus! I'm sorry!
- Watch your floorcraft, spasmo!

267
00:23:25,670 --> 00:23:29,162
What, you think you own this floor? I'll
have a bruise the size of Texas tomorrow!

268
00:23:29,241 --> 00:23:31,709
- Go away!
- Go away? You go away!

269
00:23:31,777 --> 00:23:34,678
Take your stupid music with you!
I can't dance to that crap.

270
00:23:34,746 --> 00:23:37,943
You just gonna stand there
and let that fat cow insult you?

271
00:23:38,016 --> 00:23:42,976
- I'm sorry, what did you say?
- Nothing. She didn't say anything.

272
00:23:53,598 --> 00:23:56,567
Sorry. These are the teeth
I wear for the Latin.

273
00:23:56,635 --> 00:23:59,570
It gets your smile out there.
Just a little bit bigger smile.

274
00:23:59,638 --> 00:24:02,471
Bam! Gets the judges right
in the eye, catches the light.

275
00:24:02,541 --> 00:24:04,202
And then the make-up -
you know the make-up.

276
00:24:04,276 --> 00:24:07,302
"Swish-butt," "Fancy pants,"
"Pinky boy"...

277
00:24:07,379 --> 00:24:10,610
All these names, all these names I've been
called ever since I was eight years old...

278
00:24:10,682 --> 00:24:13,776
and dancing around
to my mother's rumba records.

279
00:24:13,852 --> 00:24:16,616
You know what
the worst of it is? Huh?

280
00:24:17,722 --> 00:24:21,988
I'm not gay. Can you imagine how much
easier my life would be if I were?

281
00:24:22,060 --> 00:24:24,187
I mean, a straight man who likes
to dance around in sequins...

282
00:24:24,262 --> 00:24:26,958
walks a very lonely road.
I got news for you.

283
00:24:27,032 --> 00:24:28,966
Look, you're not gonna
tell anybody in the office, are you?

284
00:24:29,034 --> 00:24:32,526
No, no, no. I wouldn't do that.
Look, I'm in the same boat, aren't I?

285
00:24:32,604 --> 00:24:34,196
No, you're not. You're not.

286
00:24:34,272 --> 00:24:36,832
- Why not?
- Because... people like you.

287
00:24:36,908 --> 00:24:38,603
You know what I mean?
You're charming.

288
00:24:38,677 --> 00:24:42,773
I'm Linky Link. They would
crucify me if they found out.

289
00:24:42,848 --> 00:24:46,284
I'm the sports trivia king,
I'm the super sports fan, you know?

290
00:24:46,351 --> 00:24:49,514
- You don't like football?
- I... You know.

291
00:24:49,588 --> 00:24:52,648
Run three yards, fall down, pile up.
Run three yards, fall down, pile up.

292
00:24:52,724 --> 00:24:56,160
I mean, you know, four months of that,
I'm ready to put a gun to my head.

293
00:24:56,228 --> 00:24:59,425
- Fooled me.
- I know. I fooled everybody.

294
00:24:59,498 --> 00:25:01,329
You know what my dream is?

295
00:25:01,399 --> 00:25:03,230
What?

296
00:25:04,269 --> 00:25:09,935
My dream... is to be able
to dance free and proud.

297
00:25:10,008 --> 00:25:13,102
Under my own name.
For all the world to see.

298
00:25:13,178 --> 00:25:15,408
That's my dream.

299
00:25:15,480 --> 00:25:17,243
Did I get it all?

300
00:25:23,255 --> 00:25:24,517
Hey, Andy. It's Bev.

301
00:25:24,589 --> 00:25:27,922
Look, I'm sorry to call you so late.
I was just trying to find John.

302
00:25:27,993 --> 00:25:33,625
Called the office at six and Betsy said
that he'd left for the day, and I was just...

303
00:25:33,698 --> 00:25:36,758
You got home by five?
How did you manage that, you lucky dog?

304
00:25:36,835 --> 00:25:40,396
Ah, there's the door.
OK. See you. Bye.

305
00:25:40,472 --> 00:25:42,201
Sorry I'm late.
I got hung up at the office.

306
00:25:42,274 --> 00:25:45,072
I wish you'd call, 'cause we were looking
all over for your car keys forever...

307
00:25:45,143 --> 00:25:48,044
- I thought you were shopping with Jenna.
- That was weeks ago.

308
00:25:48,113 --> 00:25:50,980
I called the office and Betsy said
you left for the day at six.

309
00:25:51,049 --> 00:25:52,983
Yeah, I did - for a sandwich.
Then I came back.

310
00:25:53,051 --> 00:25:56,077
Oh. Well, I called your private line
a few times, nobody picked up.

311
00:25:56,154 --> 00:25:58,418
That's because I wasn't working
in my office, I was in Andy's.

312
00:25:58,490 --> 00:26:00,117
Oh. How is Andy?

313
00:26:00,191 --> 00:26:04,423
We're working on a really big
estate plan together.

314
00:26:04,496 --> 00:26:06,896
- So he was there?
- What?

315
00:26:06,965 --> 00:26:08,626
Was Andy there?

316
00:26:08,700 --> 00:26:10,429
Why are you asking me
all these questions?

317
00:26:10,502 --> 00:26:12,436
I don't know.

318
00:26:13,572 --> 00:26:17,770
Anyway, I stopped off for a bite
on the way home with Link Peterson.

319
00:26:17,842 --> 00:26:20,436
Remember him?
Interesting guy.

320
00:26:21,112 --> 00:26:23,842
Not what you'd think.

321
00:26:23,915 --> 00:26:26,315
- How was your day?
- Great.

322
00:26:33,959 --> 00:26:37,486
One, two, three, four...

323
00:26:38,797 --> 00:26:41,163
One, two, three...

324
00:26:57,949 --> 00:26:59,416
Mom?

325
00:27:00,085 --> 00:27:02,417
Dad's acting weird.

326
00:27:10,195 --> 00:27:15,394
They met five years ago
in a chat room for gardeners.

327
00:27:17,802 --> 00:27:20,066
He says they're in love.

328
00:27:20,839 --> 00:27:23,137
He's moving out Saturday.

329
00:27:23,208 --> 00:27:26,234
He'll be back.
He loves those kids.

330
00:27:26,311 --> 00:27:28,370
I thought we were happy.

331
00:27:28,446 --> 00:27:30,710
He seemed happy to me.

332
00:27:31,916 --> 00:27:34,441
I didn't know anything.

333
00:27:36,254 --> 00:27:37,881
I didn't know.

334
00:27:46,698 --> 00:27:48,757
Oh...

335
00:27:48,833 --> 00:27:50,892
Hi.

336
00:27:50,969 --> 00:27:55,997
I, uh... I give free consultations
during my lunch hour.

337
00:27:56,074 --> 00:27:58,474
You sure you don't
wanna come in?

338
00:27:59,344 --> 00:28:01,175
So he comes home late
on Wednesdays,

339
00:28:01,246 --> 00:28:03,214
and when he comes home
his shirts smell like perfume.

340
00:28:03,281 --> 00:28:06,546
He's been seen making strange body
movements and you feel he has a secret.

341
00:28:06,618 --> 00:28:09,212
- That's correct.
- Ever think about just asking him?

342
00:28:09,287 --> 00:28:12,848
- Yes, I've thought about it...
- Mrs. Clark...

343
00:28:12,924 --> 00:28:17,258
things happen in long marriages.
To the best of people.

344
00:28:17,328 --> 00:28:20,229
And sometimes the thing that happens
doesn't mean anything.

345
00:28:20,298 --> 00:28:23,199
Doesn't need an investigator, just needs
somebody to look the other way for a while.

346
00:28:23,268 --> 00:28:27,830
My husband is a serious man, Mr. Devine.
If he's having an affair, it is not casual.

347
00:28:27,906 --> 00:28:30,602
In which case,
the sooner I know, the better.

348
00:28:32,277 --> 00:28:36,111
All right. Give me a moment while
I call in my associate, Mr. Harcourt.

349
00:28:36,181 --> 00:28:38,172
Scottie!

350
00:28:39,551 --> 00:28:41,314
Scottie Harcourt,
this is Mrs. Clark.

351
00:28:41,386 --> 00:28:43,786
She suspects
her husband's up to no good.

352
00:28:43,855 --> 00:28:48,189
"To catch a husband is an art.
To hold him is a job."

353
00:28:48,259 --> 00:28:51,751
Simone de Beauvoir said that.
It's very nice to meet you, Mrs. Clark.

354
00:28:51,830 --> 00:28:52,819
Same here.

355
00:28:52,897 --> 00:28:55,889
I think we can start this investigation
without too much cost to Mrs. Clark.

356
00:28:55,967 --> 00:29:01,098
Yes. Follow that husband around for a few
days, take some pictures, see what's up.

357
00:29:01,172 --> 00:29:02,935
But I have to warn you,
if it goes to trial it's gonna be...

358
00:29:03,007 --> 00:29:05,237
Trial?

359
00:29:06,544 --> 00:29:09,012
In the event of a divorce.

360
00:29:09,080 --> 00:29:10,877
But we don't know if
he's having an affair.

361
00:29:10,949 --> 00:29:16,182
I mean, he could just be
involved with... I don't know...

362
00:29:17,155 --> 00:29:20,124
people who get together
to invest things,

363
00:29:20,191 --> 00:29:26,027
and... and the place that they
invest things is... filled with potpourri,

364
00:29:26,097 --> 00:29:31,228
and that's why his shirts smell so sweet
when he comes home. It's possible.

365
00:29:31,302 --> 00:29:33,600
Yeah, it's possible.
It's possible.

366
00:29:33,671 --> 00:29:38,335
It's possible we could find your husband
neck-deep in potpourri, investing things.

367
00:29:38,409 --> 00:29:40,400
Not likely.

368
00:29:44,482 --> 00:29:47,076
Look, this is what we'll do.

369
00:29:49,420 --> 00:29:51,684
We start out gently.

370
00:29:56,161 --> 00:29:58,186
We look for the potpourri.

371
00:29:58,263 --> 00:30:03,758
And if we find it, and it smells like flowers,
then 2,000 ought to cover my time.

372
00:30:03,835 --> 00:30:08,135
But if we find the potpourri and there's
something big and stinky in the pot,

373
00:30:08,206 --> 00:30:11,698
then you and I renegotiate, OK?
That sound good?

374
00:30:11,776 --> 00:30:13,767
OK.

375
00:30:19,584 --> 00:30:21,449
- Hey.
- Hi.

376
00:30:21,519 --> 00:30:23,783
- How you doin'?
- Good.

377
00:30:25,990 --> 00:30:28,857
- I can tell, you know.
- Tell what?

378
00:30:28,927 --> 00:30:31,725
That you've been dancing.
Your posture, it's a dead giveaway.

379
00:30:31,796 --> 00:30:33,957
- You're kidding.
- No.

380
00:30:35,967 --> 00:30:38,595
- How much you been practicing, anyway?
- Just in class.

381
00:30:38,670 --> 00:30:42,606
No. Should be five to one.
Five-to-one ratio.

382
00:30:42,674 --> 00:30:46,542
Five hours of practice
for every one hour of class.

383
00:30:49,013 --> 00:30:52,244
Doctor Dance has an open
dance party every Thursday.

384
00:30:52,317 --> 00:30:55,718
Anybody can go and practice.
Even you.

385
00:30:57,322 --> 00:30:59,517
Ballroom is all or nothing, John.

386
00:30:59,591 --> 00:31:02,321
I'm draggin' your ass out of class
and onto a real dance floor.

387
00:31:02,393 --> 00:31:05,328
We'll go straight there
after work.

388
00:31:05,396 --> 00:31:07,694
- Link?
- Yeah?

389
00:31:07,765 --> 00:31:10,199
Can you really tell?

390
00:31:10,268 --> 00:31:11,963
Yeah.

391
00:31:33,992 --> 00:31:36,187
Having fun?

392
00:31:36,261 --> 00:31:39,753
- What are you doing here?
- Spying.

393
00:32:06,958 --> 00:32:09,256
Excuse me, we were
dancing together.

394
00:32:09,327 --> 00:32:12,091
Dude, she does not wanna
dance with you. Now back off.

395
00:32:12,163 --> 00:32:14,063
Hey, you know, I...

396
00:32:18,836 --> 00:32:22,602
Link always insists on dancing
with the youngest girls.

397
00:32:22,674 --> 00:32:27,976
I've never seen him with his perfect
partner. Not that those are easy to find.

398
00:32:28,046 --> 00:32:30,014
Have you ever found one?

399
00:32:30,081 --> 00:32:34,984
Once. He was my
dancing partner for 15 years.

400
00:32:35,053 --> 00:32:37,920
- We were husband and wife for 14.
- Wow.

401
00:32:37,989 --> 00:32:42,688
Yeah. He was my perfect partner.
Doesn't happen twice in a lifetime.

402
00:32:42,760 --> 00:32:45,695
I'm lucky it even happened once.

403
00:32:45,763 --> 00:32:46,661
Ah!

404
00:32:46,731 --> 00:32:51,395
At last, a song I know.
Oh, I love this song.

405
00:32:52,170 --> 00:32:54,297
♪ Da da-da da...

406
00:32:54,372 --> 00:32:58,968
♪ Shall we still be together
With our arms around each other

407
00:32:59,043 --> 00:33:03,275
♪ And shall you be
my new romance?

408
00:33:03,348 --> 00:33:07,944
♪ On the clear understanding
that this kind of thing can happen

409
00:33:08,019 --> 00:33:12,251
♪ Shall we dance, shall we dance,
shall we dance?

410
00:33:13,091 --> 00:33:16,857
It's The King and I.</i> Yul Brynner
and Deborah Kerr. Do you remember that?

411
00:33:16,928 --> 00:33:20,193
They held hands like this...
Oh, come on, John, let's try it.

412
00:33:20,264 --> 00:33:22,926
- No. No, no, no, I can't. No way. I can't.
- Why not?

413
00:33:23,001 --> 00:33:28,029
- Oh, John, come on. Come on.
- I don't... No, I don't want to...

414
00:33:34,912 --> 00:33:37,244
Let go, John.

415
00:33:44,055 --> 00:33:46,046
That's it, John.

416
00:33:50,128 --> 00:33:51,152
Whoa!

417
00:33:51,229 --> 00:33:53,925
- Sorry! I wasn't watching.
- Hi! How are you?

418
00:33:53,998 --> 00:33:57,957
- It doesn't matter. We're finished anyway.
- What do you mean?

419
00:33:58,036 --> 00:34:00,061
No offense, but I can't be
your dance partner.

420
00:34:00,138 --> 00:34:01,901
- Why?
- You're too much of a freak.

421
00:34:01,973 --> 00:34:05,739
I mean, look at your palms. They're
bright orange from self-tanning lotion.

422
00:34:05,810 --> 00:34:11,407
Don't you know you're supposed to wash
your hands after you use that stuff?

423
00:34:16,687 --> 00:34:18,780
Excuse me.

424
00:34:44,248 --> 00:34:47,513
Miss Mitzi couldn't make it tonight,
so I'll be your teacher.

425
00:34:47,585 --> 00:34:49,212
I'm Paulina.

426
00:34:49,287 --> 00:34:54,315
And you're...
Chic and Vern and...

427
00:34:56,527 --> 00:34:59,621
- Tom.
- John. It's John.

428
00:35:01,799 --> 00:35:04,165
What would you like
to work on tonight?

429
00:35:04,235 --> 00:35:09,935
Well, in my opinion - Chic - I think since
we're beginners, a good idea would be...

430
00:35:10,007 --> 00:35:11,804
Waltz.

431
00:35:11,876 --> 00:35:14,071
Maybe the waltz.

432
00:35:17,181 --> 00:35:19,649
OK. Um...

433
00:35:19,717 --> 00:35:24,086
I'll work with you one at a time
and you can be first.

434
00:35:25,089 --> 00:35:27,250
OK. All right.

435
00:36:09,200 --> 00:36:11,134
- Oops.
- I'm sorry.

436
00:37:04,589 --> 00:37:07,422
So are you really
a reporter for The Times</i>.

437
00:37:07,491 --> 00:37:10,016
Or are you just pickin' up on her,
like everybody else?

438
00:37:10,094 --> 00:37:13,086
I'm a reporter.
Plus, she's not my type.

439
00:37:13,164 --> 00:37:16,827
I like a woman built for comfort,
not for speed.

440
00:37:18,135 --> 00:37:22,936
Really? Why don't you put the camera
down and take me out on the dance floor?

441
00:37:23,007 --> 00:37:27,137
Two reasons: I'm working
and this is not my type of dance.

442
00:37:27,211 --> 00:37:28,872
Well, how do you know
if you've never tried?

443
00:37:28,946 --> 00:37:32,211
Come on, put the camera down.
Come on, give me a shot.

444
00:37:32,283 --> 00:37:33,682
Oh, dear!

445
00:37:33,751 --> 00:37:35,810
Sorry, sorry!

446
00:37:38,422 --> 00:37:40,788
- I'm sorry.
- It's gonna stain.

447
00:37:40,858 --> 00:37:44,385
Don't... worry.
I'll take care of it.

448
00:38:05,449 --> 00:38:08,043
- Would you like to use this?
- Excuse me?

449
00:38:08,119 --> 00:38:10,747
Just to wipe your coat, or...

450
00:38:12,256 --> 00:38:16,420
Go ahead, just take it.
Please. Go ahead.

451
00:38:16,494 --> 00:38:20,225
- It's silly, but it's my favorite coat.
- I'm sorry.

452
00:38:20,298 --> 00:38:22,289
It's vintage.

453
00:38:23,301 --> 00:38:26,828
But this part's real suede,
so now it's ruined.

454
00:38:26,904 --> 00:38:29,464
You sure?
Maybe they can fix that.

455
00:38:29,540 --> 00:38:32,976
No. I know about stains. It's...

456
00:38:33,978 --> 00:38:36,105
You know, I never understood that.
I never understood -

457
00:38:36,180 --> 00:38:40,480
live cows get dirty all the time,
they don't get stained.

458
00:38:40,551 --> 00:38:44,544
All that leather stands in the mud,
nothing happens. Go figure. What is that?

459
00:38:45,790 --> 00:38:47,849
Exactly.

460
00:38:50,027 --> 00:38:53,656
Get a little sauce
on your coat and look.

461
00:38:53,731 --> 00:38:55,892
- Why is that?
- I don't know.

462
00:38:55,966 --> 00:38:59,902
We'll have to ask the
next cow that comes by.

463
00:39:09,980 --> 00:39:15,646
A man with a handkerchief. Wow.
I didn't know they made those anymore.

464
00:39:21,459 --> 00:39:27,591
I haven't eaten yet. If you haven't eaten yet,
maybe we can go and... get a bite.

465
00:39:28,432 --> 00:39:30,923
